{"timestamp": "2025-12-05 13:46:24.667536", "event": "llm_end", "text": "Diagnostic report — RIP/VPN mini-Internet\nPrepared observations date: current lab state\n\nExecutive summary\n- Network reachability tests show all hosts (including non‑VPN hosts) can reach the external web servers in 20.0.0.0/24. In particular, hosts that are not supposed to have direct access to web_server_1_1/1_2 (per design) can reach them.\n- The WireGuard VPN interface on the VPN client (host_1) and the VPN server (vpn_server_1) are present and UP, but show zero traffic on wg0 — the VPN is not carrying traffic.\n- Root cause (most likely): the 20.0.0.0/24 web server LAN is being advertised and routed across the RIP domain (via external_router_1), so traffic from internal hosts uses the normal routed path to the servers instead of traversing the VPN. In addition host_1 has no specific route that forces 20.0.0.0/24 over wg0, so its default path sends traffic over the local WAN (10.0.0.1) rather than the tunnel.\n- Secondary configuration oddity: gateway_router's FRR configuration contains \"network None\" (an apparent misconfiguration) while external_router_1 explicitly runs RIP for 20.0.0.0/24 — this combination appears to have resulted in the server LAN being reachable throughout the internal network.\n\nDetailed findings and evidence\n\n1) Reachability (behavior vs. intended design)\n- From the reachability dump:\n  - host_1 -> web_server_1_2 (20.0.0.4): success (0% loss).\n  - host_2 (non‑VPN) -> web_server_1_2: success (0% loss).\n  - Many hosts and servers can ping across 20.0.0.0/24 and 20.0.1.0/24 with low latency and no loss.\n- Interpretation: Web servers in 20.0.0.0/24 are reachable by hosts that are not using the VPN. This violates the stated design requirement that web_server_1_1/1_2 be reachable only via the VPN overlay.\n\n2) WireGuard (VPN) state and usage\n- host_1 ifconfig/ip addr:\n  - wg0 exists, UP, inet 172.16.1.11/24.\n  - wg0 packet counters: RX packets 0, TX packets 0.\n  - Host route table: default via 10.0.0.1 (no specific route for 20.0.0.0/24 via wg0).\n  - Evidence: host_1 ip_route includes default via 10.0.0.1 and 172.16.1.0/24 via wg0, but no route forcing 20.0.0.0/24 to use wg0.\n- vpn_server_1 ifconfig/ip addr:\n  - wg0 exists, UP, inet 172.16.1.1/24.\n  - wg0 packet counters: RX packets 0, TX packets 0.\n- Interpretation: The WG interfaces are up but show zero handshake or data packets, indicating the tunnel is not being used (no observed WG traffic). Since host_1 is reaching web servers while wg0 shows zero traffic, traffic is taking the regular routed path, not the VPN.\n\n3) Routing protocol and FRR configurations\n- external_router_1 (FRR running):\n  - router rip has \"network 192.168.0.0/16\" and \"network 20.0.0.0/24\", redistribute static.\n  - Evidence: external_router_1 explicitly includes 20.0.0.0/24 in RIP.\n- gateway_router (FRR running):\n  - router rip block shows \"network 192.168.0.0/16\" and \"network None\" — \"network None\" is anomalous (likely a config mistake).\n  - Despite config oddity, gateway_router's route table contains 20.0.0.0/24 via external_router_1 (it learned that route).\n- Other internal routers (router1, router2) advertise their 10.0.X.0/24 networks under RIP; RIP is present network‑wide.\n- Router routing tables show paths to 20.0.0.0/24 propagated through RIP (e.g., router1 has 20.0.0.0/24 nhid via 192.168.0.13).\n- Interpretation: external_router_1 is advertising the 20.0.0.0/24 server LAN into the RIP domain, and other routers have installed routes to that prefix. This makes the server LAN reachable by ordinary routing across the internal routers.\n\n4) Localization of the misconfiguration / faulty components\n- External router: external_router_1 — configured to run RIP for 20.0.0.0/24 (explicitly in its running-config). This is the origin of the prefix advertisement.\n  - Evidence: external_router_1 running-config includes \"network 20.0.0.0/24\".\n- Gateway/router domain: gateway_router (and the rest of the RIP domain) is accepting and propagating those RIP routes (gateway_router shows the learned route and other routers show nhid entries pointing to gateway addresses).\n  - Evidence: gateway_router route table contains 20.0.0.0/24 via 192.168.0.17; router1/2 routing tables show nhid via gateway addresses.\n- VPN client: host_1 — wg0 present but unused and no routing rule to send 20.0.0.0/24 via wg0.\n  - Evidence: wg0 packet counters on host_1 are zero, default route points to 10.0.0.1 (local router), and reachability shows direct connectivity to 20.0.0.4.\n\nProbable root cause(s)\n- Primary root cause: unintended global routing of the 20.0.0.0/24 server LAN through the RIP domain (advertised by external_router_1 and learned/propagated by gateway_router and the internal routers). Because the servers' prefixes are visible in the routing domain, hosts can reach those servers via normal IP routing without using the VPN overlay.\n- Contributing root cause: the WireGuard VPN overlay is not actually carrying traffic — the client and server have WG interfaces up but no handshake/data (zero packet counters). Possible specific causes (not confirmed by current evidence) include:\n  - The host_1 has no policy/route to force 20.0.0.0/24 traffic into the wg0 tunnel (its routing table lacks such entries); and/or\n  - WireGuard peer configuration/allowed IPs are incomplete or the tunnel handshake is not established (no wg tx/rx seen).\n- Configuration anomaly: gateway_router's FRR config shows \"network None\" which is likely a misconfiguration (may have been intended to include the 20.0.0.0/24 or other networks but currently reads oddly). Regardless of that string, gateway_router did learn and propagate the 20.0.0.0/24 route from external_router_1.\n\nOperational impact\n- Access control requirement violated: resources that should be reachable only via the VPN (web_server_1_1/1_2) are directly reachable by any host on the internal RIP domain. This breaks isolation and potentially exposes private services.\n- VPN overlay unused: the intended secure path (WireGuard) is not in effect — sensitive traffic may be traversing non‑encrypted links.\n- Potential security and privacy exposure: service isolation and confidentiality goals are not being met.\n\nSummary list — evidence snippets\n- host_1 wg0 counters: RX 0 TX 0 (wg0 present but no packets).\n- host_1 routing: default via 10.0.0.1 (no 20.0.0.0/24 via wg0 entry).\n- reachability: host_2 -> web_server_1_2 (20.0.0.4) = successful ping (non‑VPN host to server).\n- external_router_1 running-config: contains \"network 20.0.0.0/24\" under router rip.\n- gateway_router running-config: \"network None\" under router rip (suspicious).\n\nConclusions (diagnostic)\n- There is a clear anomaly: servers intended to be reachable only through the VPN are reachable via the normal routed domain.\n- The most likely technical cause is RIP propagation of the 20.0.0.0/24 prefix (external_router_1 advertising it) combined with host_1 not routing server traffic into the WG tunnel. In short: routing leakage + unused VPN tunnel.\n- A configuration problem exists in multiple places: the RIP advertisement for server networks and the lack of host-side routes/policy to use the VPN.\n\n(End of diagnostic report — no remediation steps included per instructions.)", "generation_info": {"finish_reason": "stop", "logprobs": null}, "invalid_tool_calls": [], "usage_metadata": {"input_tokens": 16329, "output_tokens": 3544, "total_tokens": 19873, "input_token_details": {"audio": 0, "cache_read": 16128}, "output_token_details": {"audio": 0, "reasoning": 1664}}}
